  "prompt": "What's the difference between harmony, rhythm and melody?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between harmony, rhythm, and melody:\n\n1. Melody:\n- The main tune or sequence of notes\n- The part of music you can hum or sing along to\n- A linear progression of musical tones that creates a recognizable musical phrase\n- Usually the most memorable part of a song\n\n2. Rhythm:\n- The pattern of sounds and silences in music\n- The beat or pulse that creates the music's timing\n- Determines how long notes are played and the overall tempo\n- Involves the timing and duration of musical sounds\n- Creates the music's sense of movement and flow\n\n3. Harmony:\n- The combination of simultaneously played notes that complement each other\n- Occurs when multiple notes are played together to create chords\n- Provides depth and richness to music\n- Supports and enhances the melody\n- Creates musical tension and resolution\n\nSimple example:\n- In a song, the lead singer's part is the melody\n- The drum beat is the rhythm\n- The background instruments playing chords are creating harmony\n\nEach element is important and works together to create a complete musical experience.",
